The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, Jan. 9: Income tax payers will be able to see details of their tax payments on the Internet from April, instead of waiting for the government to confirm it months after the filing of returns. After putting in place the tax information network last year, the finance ministry is planning to introduce an electronic PAN book, which would furnish details of tax payments by individual assessees, sources said. National Securities Depository Ltd has been asked to start the online PAN book from April to enable assesses to see their tax filing record instantly.

 New Delhi, Jan. 9: In an effort to speed up fund transfers, the Reserve bank of India (RBI) is working on a system to enable encashment of multi-city cheques within a day or two. Days are not far when a person can transfer funds through the nearby bank ATMs also, said R. Gandhi, chief general manager of Reserve Bank.

 New Delhi, Jan. 9: The ministry of heavy industries has formulated a revival plan for Tyre Corporation of India and will place it before the Board for Reconstruction of Public Sector Enterprises within a month.

 New Delhi, Jan. 9: Telecom tribunal TDSAT has issued an order, which says there is no scope for arbitration in telecom and broadcasting disputes under the Trai Act 1997. 

 London, Jan. 9: The UK-based Caparo group plans two sheet metal pressing and welding plants in Haryana and a facility in Rajasthan to make fasteners, this year, said CEO Angad Paul.




